[1] USA
[A]
Date: Mon 5 Dec 2022
Source: KIRO7 [edited]
https://www.kiro7.com/news/local/influenza-has-already-killed-least-13-state-earliest-outbreak-years/I6PWKZKTIRCRLI6LBWAQ5OSVCQ/


The flu is hitting the state [of Washington] hard, and already 13 people have died from the flu. Nearly half of them were in King and Snohomish counties. So far this fall, influenza has killed 4 people in King County, including 2 young children.

On Monday [5 Dec 2022], Snohomish County announced that 2 people had died from the flu there. Infectious disease experts are expecting the worst as the holidays approach.

The flu is hitting especially early this year [2022]. And that is what is setting off alarm bells in the medical community and keeping pharmacies busy.

"My sister has a friend who's in the hospital right now," said [LR], standing outside of Katterman's Pharmacy on Sand Point Way.

She says her sister's friend and news reports about the flu have scared her. "My sister got upset with [me] this morning for not having my vaccine," admitted [LR]. "And so, I am here."

Dr. Eric Chow is chief of Public Health, Seattle & King County's Communicable Disease Epidemiology Division.

"What I'm seeing right now is alarming," he said. Chow says this is the worst influenza outbreak in at least 4 years. "Since the beginning of September [2022], we've seen surges in respiratory syncytial virus, or RSV, infections," said Chow. "On the heels of that, we've seen early increased activity and influenza. And we're always concerned about the return of COVID-19 and increased activity, especially how it will impact communities as well as put additional stress on our healthcare facilities."

Just 3 weeks ago, King County laboratories were reporting that 13.2% of samples were coming back positive for influenza. It was up again the next week. The last time the numbers were reported, nearly 1/3 of the tests were positive for the flu.

"That's why we have to do our due diligence," said Chow. "Get our vaccines, reduce the chance of infection as much as we can."

"It doesn't sound good," said [LR]. "I think I'll just wear my mask and try to stay home a lot."

According to Chow, [LR] has the right idea. Chow says he knows no one wants to hear that, but you need to mask up, wash your hands, and isolate whenever you feel sick.

This wave of the flu could go on for some time. The flu usually doesn't peak until February.

[Byline: Deborah Horne]

